{"meta":{"spec_version":"0.3","created":"2025-01-01T00:00:00Z","author":"OpenChronology Demo"},"event":{"id":"holy-roman-empire","type":"era","content":{"title":"Holy Roman Empire","date_label":"962 CE – 1806 CE","description":"Founded when **Pope John XII crowned Otto I** as emperor in 962 CE, the Holy Roman Empire was a complex of territories in central Europe, nominally under the authority of a Holy Roman Emperor elected by powerful princes.\n\nVoltaire famously observed it was *\"neither holy, nor Roman, nor an empire\"* — an apt description of its famously decentralized structure, constant tension between papal and imperial authority, and failure to consolidate into a unified state in the way that France and England did.\n\nDespite its structural paradoxes, it was the dominant political framework of central Europe for over eight centuries, encompassing modern Germany, Austria, Switzerland, the Czech Republic, and parts of France and Italy.","description_format":"markdown","tags":["holy-roman-empire","germany","papacy","medieval","feudalism"],"sources":[{"title":"Holy Roman Empire — Encyclopedia Britannica","url":"https://www.britannica.com/place/Holy-Roman-Empire"}]},"temporal":{"calendar":"gregorian","start_value":"962","end_value":"1806","precision":"year"},"significance":{"value":900,"temporal_scope":"centuries","geographic_scope":"central-europe"}}}
